Security cameras.

A security camera is a watching trap that doesn't hurt the player directly — it raises the alarm and calls in reinforcements. Mounted on a single tile, it swings back and forth scanning the area in front of it, and if it catches the player in its gaze it sounds an alert and starts summoning human enemies to hunt them down. Unlike most traps, a camera has health and a level: it can be shot out like an enemy, and bringing it down both silences the alarm and rewards the player with experience. A camera turns a room into a stealth problem, where the player has to slip past its sweep or destroy it before it spots them.

How a security camera works.

A camera sits on a single tile and sweeps, turning to face one way and then the other on its turn interval, playing its turning sound each time it pivots. At any moment it can only see in the direction it currently faces, out to its seeing range, and within its depth range to either side. The player is spotted when they're on the faced side within that range — so timing a crossing for when the camera looks away, or staying out of its range, keeps them unseen.

The moment the camera spots the player it plays its alert. A few seconds later, if it still hasn't been dealt with, it raises a looping alarm and begins spawning human enemies near itself, one after another, to chase the player down — so a camera left alone after it's seen you becomes a steady stream of guards. The camera carries health, a level, and an experience value, and it can be damaged by weapons and explosives like any enemy. When its health reaches zero it plays its death clip, stops spawning and alarming, and awards experience based on its level. On 3d maps the camera also checks the player's height against its seeing range.

Security camera fields.

The security camera form takes the following:

Coordinates. An x and a y (and a z on 3d maps) — the tile the camera is mounted on.

X seeing range. How far ahead, along the x axis, the camera can spot the player. Defaults to the map's full width.
Y seeing range. How far to either side, along the y axis, the camera can spot the player. Defaults to the map's full depth.
Z seeing range. On 3d maps, how far through height the camera can spot the player. Defaults to the map's full height.

Speed. The number of milliseconds between each turn of the sweep, so a smaller number makes the camera scan back and forth faster.

Health. How much damage the camera can absorb before it's destroyed.

Level. The camera's level, which scales the experience it awards when destroyed.
Xp. The base experience granted for destroying the camera, before the level scaling.

Direction. Which way the camera faces first, left or right; it sweeps back and forth from there.

Camera sound (a folder name from the camera sounds list, or none). The audio theme; the bundle supplies the turning cue, the alert when it first spots the player, the looping alarm, the hurt clip, and the death clip. Pick none for a silent camera.

Auditioning sounds in the builder.

While the camera sound list is focused in the form, press space to hear the highlighted theme's hurt clip, hold control and press L to hear its turning cue, and hold control and press H to hear its alert.

Authoring security cameras by hand.

If you edit main.sif directly, a security camera is written under the name camera: camera x y xrange yrange direction speed health level xp cameratype. On 3d maps a z follows the y and a z range follows the y range: camera x y z xrange yrange zrange direction speed health level xp cameratype. The ranges, speed, health, level, and xp are numbers, direction is 1 for left or 2 for right, and the camera sound must match a camera sounds folder name or the word none.
